F48-A75C81D86AE8</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>James</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Allister</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>McGregor</gtr:surname><gtr:orcidId>0000-0001-5839-002X</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF015135%2F1"><gtr:id>878BDEA5-6EAB-4CB3-986F-FDCC9E489DDC</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Political and Policy Implications of Wellbeing</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F015135/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>'Wellbeing' has emerged as an increasingly prominent feature of policy and public political debate, both in the UK and internationally. The ESRC funded Wellbeing in Developing Countries research group (WeD) has elaborated a conceptual framework with which to comprehend and study the social and cultural construction of wellbeing (Gough and McGregor 2007). This fellowship enables the further exploration of the ways in which the notion of wellbeing and the methodology for researching it can be of value to development policy-makers and practitioners.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />&amp;nbsp;
&lt;br />
&lt;br />A practical and operational concept of wellbeing challenges us to consider how we are to live together in society. It focuses us on the perceived legitimacy of systems of governance. Engagement with development practitioners, policy-makers and academics concerned with development policy will explore the implications of a concept of wellbeing for how they think about the relationship between governance and poverty. It will explore the ways in which the wellbeing approach relates to their conception of their roles and their policies. The fellowship year will focus on two levels: a global network of policy-makers and practitioners from a range of international, national and non-governmental development agencies; and ongoing research in Thailand on the wellbeing agenda of local government.
&lt;br />
